The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Pervez thanks India for help

 OUR CORRESPONDENT

 Islamabad, Oct. 13: Almost 24 hours after the first Indian aircraft with relief landed here, Pervez Musharraf thanked Manmohan Singh yesterday and said Pakistan has accepted his offer of assistance in certain forms.

 May I also say that the Indian Premier was kind enough to ring me up and offer all possible assistance. We express our gratitude to him and (have) accepted Indian aid in certain forms and informed him accordingly, Musharraf told Pakistan through a televised address.

 The President also appealed to the world community and his countrymen for more financial assistance to overcome the impact of Saturdays 7.6-magnitude earthquake that killed tens of thousands in northern Pakistan and Pakistan Kashmir.

 I appeal to the international community to donate funds and give financial assistance, he said.

 Several countries have already committed $600 million and sent rescue teams with helicopters and tons of relief goods, including tents, blankets, medicines and high-energy food products.

 The Pakistan President specifically mentioned Turkey, the UAE, the US, the UK, Saudi Arabia, China, Germany, Russia, France, Japan, Switzerland, Spain, Iran, Azerbaijan, Hungary and Bangladesh for their generous help.

 US secretary of state Condoleezza Rice, who had flown into Islamabad to express her countrys sympathy and condolences for the quake affectees, also assured Musharraf and Pakistan Prime Minister Shaukat Aziz of greater assistance, including more helicopters and technical help like equipment to remove dead bodies from the debris and clear roads in PoK and adjoining northern areas.




